{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486907","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486907"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:48:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:48:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"203"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"203","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/203"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.33,0.2,0.21,0.21]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"203"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103176"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"203","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/203"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"203"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85617"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"247"},{"type":"tags","id":"320"},{"type":"tags","id":"1217"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"11063"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"31585"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31586"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39122"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45046"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103176","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103176"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 36-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-week history of a painless swelling in her left breast. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Examination of both breasts and axillae is normal apart from a small, mobile, non-tender lump in the upper outer quadrant of her left breast. An ultrasound confirms the presence of a 15 mm simple cyst.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Excisional biopsy","Reassurance and no follow-up","Repeat ultrasound in three months","Repeat ultrasound in six months","Aspiration"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with an incidental finding of a simple breast cyst, which has typical benign features on ultrasound. \u003Cstrong\u003EReassurance and no follow-up\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management as simple breast cysts are common benign findings that do not increase cancer risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExcisional biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E would be unnecessarily invasive for a simple cyst with typical ultrasound features. Surgical intervention is rarely indicated for breast cysts and should be reserved for cases where there is diagnostic uncertainty or concerning features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E at either \u003Cstrong\u003Ethree months\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Esix months\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary for a simple cyst with typical features. This would lead to unnecessary anxiety and healthcare costs without providing clinical benefit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspiration\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated for asymptomatic simple cysts. It may be considered if the cyst is causing significant symptoms such as pain or if there are atypical features on imaging that require cytological analysis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBreast cysts affect approximately 7% of women and are often hormone-responsive, meaning they can fluctuate in size throughout the menstrual cycle. When a cyst shows typical features on ultrasound (well-circumscribed, anechoic, thin-walled), no intervention or follow-up is required. The patient should be advised about normal breast awareness and to return if there are any concerning changes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Simple breast cysts with typical ultrasound features do not require intervention or follow-up","Breast cysts are common, affecting 7% of women, and can fluctuate with hormonal changes","Asymptomatic simple cysts do not increase breast cancer risk"],"references":["Brennan M, Houssami N, French J. Management of benign breast conditions - breast lumps and lesions. Aust Fam Physician. 2005 Apr;34(4), 253\u2013255. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/2ec39a59-5c99-4242-aa4f-0e7a48bd4690/200504brennan.pdf","Cancer Australia. The investigation of a new breast symptom \u2013 a guide for General Practitioners [Internet]. Surry Hills NSW: Cancer Australia; 2017. Available from:\u00a0https://canceraustralia.gov.au/sites/default/files/publications/investigation-new-breast-symptom-guide-general-practitioners/pdf/2017_inbs_gp_card.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85617"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"203"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85617","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85617"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-20T14:06:40+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-17T07:23:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"203"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103176"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdA